from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

x = data.drop(['SalePrice'], axis=1)
y = data['SalePrice']

xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(
	x, y, train_size=0.8, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

# Assuming mape_values is a list of your MAPE values
mape_values = [mape_svr, mape_lr, mape_knn, mape_gb, mape_dt, mape_rf]

# Model names
models = ['SVR', 'Linear Regression', 'KNN', 'Gradient Boosting', 'Decision Tree', 'Random Forest']
color=['skyblue']
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.bar(models, mape_values, color=color)
plt.xlabel('Models')
plt.ylabel('Mean Absolute Percentage Error')
plt.title('Model Performance')
plt.show()
In[91]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Dictionary of models
models = {
    'Random Forest': rf,
    'Decision Tree': dt,
    'Gradient Boosting': gb,
    'KNN': knn,
}

# Dictionary of MAPE values
models_mape = {
    'Random Forest': mape_rf,
    'Decision Tree': mape_dt,
    'Gradient Boosting': mape_gb,
    'KNN': mape_knn,
}

# Create a line plot for each model
for model_name in models.keys():
    # Predict values
    model = models[model_name]
    Y_pred = model.predict(xtest)

    # Create a line plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.plot(ytest.values, label='Actual', color='blue')
    plt.plot(Y_pred, label='Predicted', color='red')
    plt.title(f'Actual vs Predicted House Prices ({model_name})')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Houses')
    plt.ylabel('House Price')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

colors = ['skyblue', 'red', 'purple', 'orange', 'yellow']

# Create a bar plot to compare MAPE values
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.bar(models_mape.keys(), models_mape.values(), color=colors)
plt.title('Model Performance Comparison')
plt.xlabel('Model')
plt.ylabel('MAPE')
plt.show()

Final Conclusion

This project focuses on developing a Machine Learning based House Price Prediction system using multiple regression algorithms. The dataset was preprocessed by handling missing values, encoding categorical variables using one-hot encoding, and applying feature scaling to improve model performance and stability. After preprocessing, the dataset was divided into training and testing sets to evaluate the model performance on unseen data.

Several machine learning models such as Linear Regression, Random Forest Regressor, Decision Tree Regressor, Gradient Boosting Regressor, K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), and Support Vector Regressor (SVR) were implemented and compared using Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) as the evaluation metric. Among all models, Support Vector Regressor (SVR) produced the best performance with approximately 17.7% prediction error, which is considered good for real-world house price prediction problems due to market variability and external influencing factors.

The results show that machine learning can effectively predict house prices based on available features and that proper preprocessing techniques such as encoding and scaling significantly improve model accuracy. This project also demonstrates the importance of comparing multiple models to select the best performing algorithm.

In future work, prediction accuracy can be improved using advanced models such as XGBoost, hyperparameter tuning techniques, and cross-validation. The model can also be deployed using web technologies such as Streamlit to create a real-time house price prediction system.
